## Common Mistakes

- Trusting Codex output without running any validation checks - always verify generated code
- Writing tests based on Codex's implementation instead of the specification, which masks bugs
- Ignoring linting warnings as 'just style issues' when many linting rules catch real bugs
- Skipping type checking for TypeScript/JavaScript projects, allowing type-related runtime errors
- Having insufficient test coverage that only validates happy-path scenarios
- Asking Codex to 'make the tests pass' without understanding the root cause of failures
- Not isolating tests properly, causing state leakage between test runs
- Deploying code that was not tested in an environment matching production


## Best Practices

- Always run the full validation pipeline (tests, linting, type checking) before deploying Codex-generated code
- Write comprehensive tests including edge cases, boundary conditions, and error handling scenarios
- Integrate validation into pre-commit hooks or CI/CD to prevent invalid code from being committed
- Treat linting errors as failures and maintain zero-error linting standards
- Enable strict type checking (TypeScript strict mode, mypy strict mode) to catch type-related bugs early
- Document validation failures and their solutions to build institutional knowledge
- Know when to reject Codex output rather than iterate - overly complex or inconsistent code should be rewritten
- Review Codex's fixes manually to ensure they address root causes, not just symptoms

